{{Infobox language family |name=Moru–Madi |region=[[Central African Republic|CAR]], [[Chad]], [[South Sudan]] |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=Eastern |child1=''[[Moru language|Moru]]'' |child2=Central Ma'di |child3=Southern Ma'di |glotto=moru1252 |glottorefname=Moru–Madi }}
The '''Moru–Madi languages''' of the [[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic language family]] are a cluster of closely related languages spoken in [[South Sudan]], the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]], and [[Uganda]]. Moru is spoken by 100,000 people, and Ma'di by twice that number. The most populous languages are [[Aringa language|Aringa]] of Uganda, with close to a million speakers, and [[Lugbara language|Lugbara]], with 1.6 million.
== The Language and the People == The languages in this cluster are found across three countries: [[Uganda]] ([[Madi language (Sudan and Uganda)|Ma'di]], [[Lugbara language|Lugbara]]); [[South Sudan]] (Lugbara, Ma'di, [[Lolu'bo]], [[Avukaya]], [[Kaliko]], [[Moru language|Moru]] and [[Logo language|Logo]]); and [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] (Lugbara, Avukaya, Kaliko and Logo). *[[Moru language|Moru]] *Central Ma'di **[[Avokaya language|Avokaya]] **[[Keliko language|Keliko]] **[[Omi language|Omi]] **[[Lugbara language|Lugbara]] (including Okollo, Ogoko, Rigbo Ma'di dialects) **[[Logo language|Logo]] **[[Aringa language|Aringa]] (Lower Lugbara) *Southern Ma'di **[[Ma'di language|Ma'di]] (incl. Moyo, Adjumani (Oyuwi), Lokai, Burulo) **[[Olu'bo language|Olu'bo]] (Lolubo)
== The name 'Madi' == The name ''Ma'di'' is used for various peoples in the region. There is tendency especially in the Acholi region of northern Uganda to refer to anyone from West Nile Region as a Ma'di, even the Kakwa. The only group in this region who are never called Ma'di are the Alur.
[[Joseph Pasquale Crazzolara]],<ref>[[Joseph Pasquale Crazzolara|Crazzolara, J. P.]] (2017). ''A study of the Logbara (Ma'di) language: Grammar and vocabulary''. Routledge. [Originally published 1960]</ref> for example, states that ''all [[Lugbara people|Logbara]] [...] agree that they are of the Ma'di nation, that they are Ma'di. They are called Ma'di by the Alur of Okooro, their immediate neighbours, in Bunyoro and Buganda.'' Similarly, the linguist [[Archibald Tucker|A. N. Tucker]] described the neighboring [[Keliko people]] who occupy the high plateau near the Logbara, as having the "real name Ma'di".<ref>The Eastern Sudanic Languages. By A. N. Tucker. vol. I. 434 pp. Oxford University Press, 1940</ref> However, the Keliko regard themselves as Keliko rather than as Ma'di.
