{{Infobox language |name=Old Japanese |nativename=上代日本語 |region=[[Japan]] |era=Evolved into [[Early Middle Japanese]] during the [[Heian period]] |familycolor=altaic |fam1=[[Japonic languages|Japonic]] <!-- Please do not add disputed classifications such as Altaic here; they are discussed in the article body, but the infobox is intended to be a concise overview of accepted facts. --> |script=''[[man'yōgana]]'' |image=Genryaku Manyosyu.JPG |imagesize= |imagealt=Manuscript in standard Chinese characters (standing for Old Japanese syllables), annotated in a cursive style |imagecaption=Manuscript of the ''[[Man'yōshū]]'', recording Old Japanese using [[Chinese characters]] |iso3=ojp |linglist=ojp |lingname={{efn|Described as "The ancestor of modern Japanese. 7th–10th centuries AD." The more usual date for the change from Old Japanese to Middle Japanese is ca. 800 (end of the Nara era).}} |notice=IPA |glotto=oldj1239 |glottorefname=Old Japanese |glottofoot=no }} {{nihongo|'''Old Japanese'''|上代日本語|Jōdai Nihon-go}} is the oldest attested stage of the [[Japanese language]]. It is attested in documents from the [[Nara period]] (8th century). It evolved into [[Early Middle Japanese]] in the succeeding [[Heian period]], although the precise separation of these two languages is controversial. Old Japanese was an early member of the [[Japonic languages|Japonic]] family; no conclusive links to other language families have been demonstrated.
Old Japanese was written using [[Chinese characters]], using an increasingly standardized and phonetic form that eventually evolved into ''[[man'yōgana]]''. Typically for a Japonic language and for a step in the evolutionary line of modern Japanese, Old Japanese was a primarily [[agglutinative language|agglutinative]] language with [[subject–object–verb]] word ordering. However, the language was marked by a few phonemic differences from later forms of Japanese, such as a simpler syllable structure and distinctions between several pairs of syllables pronounced identically in Early Middle Japanese and later. The phonetic realization of this differentiation is uncertain.
==Sources and dating== [[File:Buddha footprint Poems Stele Total.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Rubbing of ''[[Bussokuseki-kahi]]'' poems carved c. 752]] Linguistic changes are gradual, and the periodization of Japanese is "both delicate and controversial", with multiple competing methods and criteria for division. For both practical and conventional reasons, these divisions often correlate to political events, particularly shifts in power or changes of capital.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=119}}
Old Japanese is usually defined as the language of the [[Nara period]] (710–794), when the capital was [[Heijō-kyō]] (present-day [[Nara, Nara|Nara]]).{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=119}}{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=1}} This is the period of the earliest connected texts in Japanese, the 112 songs included in the ''[[Kojiki]]'' (712). The other major literary sources of the period are the 128 songs included in the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (720) and the ''[[Man'yōshū]]'' (c. 759), a compilation of over 4,500 poems.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=17}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=24}} Shorter samples are 25 poems in the ''[[Fudoki]]'' (720) and the 21 poems of the ''[[Bussokuseki-kahi]]'' (c. 752). The latter has the virtue of being an original inscription, whereas for all the other texts the oldest surviving manuscripts are the results of centuries of copying, with the attendant risk of scribal errors.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=19–20}} Prose texts are more limited, but are thought to reflect the syntax of Old Japanese more accurately than verse. The most important are the 27 ''[[Norito]]'' (liturgies) recorded in the ''[[Engishiki]]'' (compiled in 927) and the 62 ''Senmyō'' (imperial edicts) recorded in the ''[[Shoku Nihongi]]'' (797).{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=24}}{{sfn|Bentley|2001|p=6}}
A limited number of Japanese words, mostly personal names and place names, are recorded phonetically in ancient Chinese texts such as the "Wei Zhi" portion of the ''[[Records of the Three Kingdoms]]'' (3rd century AD), but the transcriptions by Chinese scholars are unreliable.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=5–8}} The oldest surviving native inscriptions, dating from the 5th or early 6th centuries, include those on the [[Suda Hachiman Shrine Mirror]], the [[Inariyama Sword]] and the [[Eta Funayama Sword]]. These inscriptions are written in [[Classical Chinese]], but contain several Japanese names transcribed phonetically using Chinese characters.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=10}}{{sfn|Seeley|1991|pp=16–25}} Such inscriptions become more common from the [[Suiko period]] (592–628).{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=12}} These fragments are usually considered a form of Old Japanese.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=66}}
==Writing system== {{main|Man'yōgana|Jōdai Tokushu Kanazukai}} Artifacts inscribed with Chinese characters dated as early as the 1st century AD have been found in Japan, but it appears that detailed knowledge of the script did not arrive in the islands until the early 5th century. According to the ''Kojiki'' and ''Nihon Shoki'', it was brought by scholars from [[Baekje]] (southwest Korea).{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=8–9}} The earliest texts found in Japan are written in [[Classical Chinese]], probably by immigrant scribes. Later "hybrid" texts show the influence of Japanese grammar, such as the [[word order]] (for example, placing the verb after the object).{{sfn|Seeley|1991|pp=25–31}}
Chinese and Koreans had long used Chinese characters to write non-Chinese terms and proper names phonetically, by selecting characters for Chinese words that sounded like each syllable. Koreans also used the characters phonetically to write Korean particles and inflections added to Chinese texts as an aid to reading ([[Idu script]]). In Japan, the practice was developed into ''[[man'yōgana]]'', a complete script for the Japanese language using Chinese characters phonetically, and the ancestor of modern [[kana]] syllabaries.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=126}} This system was already in use in the verse parts of the ''[[Kojiki]]'' (712) and the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (720).{{sfn|Seeley|1991|pp=41–49}}{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=18–20, 28–40}} For example, the first line of the first poem in the ''Kojiki'' was written with five characters:{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=1, 18, 22}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=19}}
{| border="0" style="margin-left: 2em;" |- ! | 夜 || 久 || 毛 || 多 || 都 |- ! [[Middle Chinese]]{{efn|Readings are given in [[Baxter's transcription for Middle Chinese]], omitting marking of tones, which are not relevant here.}} | ''yae'' || ''kjuw'' || ''maw'' || ''ta'' || ''tu'' |- ! Old Japanese | colspan="3" | ''ya-kumo''<sub>1</sub> || colspan="2" | ''tatu'' |- ! | colspan="3" | eight-cloud || colspan="2" | rise.{{sc|adn}} |- ! | colspan="5" | 'many clouds rising' |}
This method of writing Japanese syllables by using characters for their Chinese sounds (''ongana'') was supplemented with indirect methods in the complex mixed script of the ''[[Man'yōshū]]'' (c. 759).{{sfn|Seeley|1991|pp=49–53}}{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=20, 24–27}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=17–20}}
===Syllables===
In ''man'yōgana'', each Old Japanese syllable was represented by a Chinese character. Although any one of several characters could be used for a given syllable, a careful analysis revealed that 88 syllables were distinguished in the ''Kojiki'':{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=49–51}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=26–27}}
{| class="wikitable" |+ Syllables in the ''Kojiki'' |- | ''a'' | ''ka'' | ''ga'' | ''sa'' | ''za'' | ''ta'' | ''da'' | ''na'' | ''pa'' | ''ba'' | ''ma'' | ''ya'' | ''ra'' | ''wa'' |- | rowspan="2" | ''i'' | ''ki''<sub>1</sub> | ''gi''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" | ''si'' | rowspan="2" | ''zi'' | rowspan="2" | ''ti'' | rowspan="2" | ''di'' | rowspan="2" | ''ni'' | ''pi''<sub>1</sub> | ''bi''<sub>1</sub> | ''mi''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" style="background-color:#ccc" | | rowspan="2" | ''ri'' | rowspan="2" | ''wi'' |- | ''ki''<sub>2</sub> | ''gi''<sub>2</sub> | ''pi''<sub>2</sub> | ''bi''<sub>2</sub> | ''mi''<sub>2</sub> |- | ''u'' | ''ku'' | ''gu'' | ''su'' | ''zu'' | ''tu'' | ''du'' | ''nu'' | ''pu'' | ''bu'' | ''mu'' | ''yu'' | ''ru'' | style="background-color:#ccc" | |- | rowspan="2" | ''e'' | ''ke''<sub>1</sub> | ''ge''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" | ''se'' | rowspan="2" | ''ze'' | rowspan="2" | ''te'' | rowspan="2" | ''de'' | rowspan="2" | ''ne'' | ''pe''<sub>1</sub> | ''be''<sub>1</sub> | ''me''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" | ''ye'' | rowspan="2" | ''re'' | rowspan="2" | ''we'' |- | ''ke''<sub>2</sub> | ''ge''<sub>2</sub> | ''pe''<sub>2</sub> | ''be''<sub>2</sub> | ''me''<sub>2</sub> |- | rowspan="2" | ''o'' | ''ko''<sub>1</sub> | ''go''<sub>1</sub> | ''so''<sub>1</sub> | ''zo''<sub>1</sub> | ''to''<sub>1</sub> | ''do''<sub>1</sub> | ''no''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" | ''po'' | rowspan="2" | ''bo'' | ''mo''<sub>1</sub> | ''yo''<sub>1</sub> | ''ro''<sub>1</sub> | rowspan="2" | ''wo'' |- | ''ko''<sub>2</sub> | ''go''<sub>2</sub> | ''so''<sub>2</sub> | ''zo''<sub>2</sub> | ''to''<sub>2</sub> | ''do''<sub>2</sub> | ''no''<sub>2</sub> | ''mo''<sub>2</sub> | ''yo''<sub>2</sub> | ''ro''<sub>2</sub> |}
The system has the same gaps of ''yi'' and ''wu'' found in later forms of Japanese. However, many syllables that have a modern ''i'', ''e'' or ''o'' occurred in two forms, termed types {{nihongo|''A''|甲|kō}} and {{nihongo|''B''|乙|otsu}}, denoted by subscripts 1 and 2 respectively in the above table.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=49–51}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=28–29}} The syllables ''mo''<sub>1</sub> and ''mo''<sub>2</sub> are not distinguished in the slightly later ''Nihon Shoki'' and ''Man'yōshū'', reducing the syllable count to 87.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=51}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=30}} All of these pairs had merged by the [[Early Middle Japanese]] of the [[Heian period]].{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=84}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=26}}
=== Transcription === Several different notations for the type A/B distinction are found in the literature, including:{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=62}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=32}} {| class="wikitable" |+ Common notations for the type A/B distinction |- ! indexed notation | i<sub>1</sub> || i<sub>2</sub> || e<sub>1</sub> || e<sub>2</sub> || o<sub>1</sub> || o<sub>2</sub> |- ! Kindaichi, Miller, Ōno | i || ï || e || ë || o || ö |- ! modified Mathias–Miller | î || ï || ê || ë || ô || ö |- ! Yale (Martin) | yi || iy || ye || ey || wo || {{underline|o}} |- ! Frellesvig and Whitman |i || wi || ye || e || wo || o |}
==Phonology== There is no consensus on the pronunciation of the syllables distinguished by ''man'yōgana''.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=2}} One difficulty is that the [[Middle Chinese]] pronunciations of the characters used are also disputed, and since their reconstruction is partly based on [[Sino-Japanese vocabulary|Sino-Japanese]] pronunciations, there is a danger of circular reasoning.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=54–55, 63–64}} Additional evidence has been drawn from phonological [[linguistic typology|typology]], subsequent developments in the Japanese pronunciation, and comparative study of the [[Ryukyuan languages]].{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=64–65}}
===Restrictions===
Old Japanese had [[open syllable]]s, of the form (C)V, subject to additional restrictions: * Words do not begin with ''r'' or the voiced plosives ''b'', ''d'', ''z'' and ''g'', with the exception of a few loanwords.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=43}} * A bare vowel does not occur except for word-initially: vowel sequences were not permitted.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=39}}
In 1934, [[Arisaka Hideyo]] proposed a set of phonological restrictions permitted in a single morpheme. ''Arisaka's Law'' states that ''-o''<sub>2</sub> is generally not found in the same morpheme as ''-a'', ''-o''<sub>1</sub> or ''-u''. Some scholars have interpreted this as a vestige of earlier [[vowel harmony]], but it is very different from patterns observed in e.g. the [[Turkic languages]].{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=44}}
===Vowels===
The Chinese characters chosen to write syllables with the Old Japanese vowel ''a'' suggest that it was an [[open vowel|open]] unrounded vowel {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=198–203}} The vowel ''u'' was a [[close rounded back vowel]] {{IPA|/u/}}, unlike the unrounded {{IPA|/ɯ/}} of Modern Standard Japanese.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=207–211}}
Several hypotheses have been advanced to explain the A/B distinctions made in ''man'yōgana''. The issue is hotly debated, and there is no consensus.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=62}} The widely accepted traditional view, first advanced by [[Kyōsuke Kindaichi]] in 1938, is that there were eight pure vowels, with the type B vowels being more central than their type A counterparts.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=55}} Others, beginning in the 1930s but more commonly since the work of Roland Lange in 1968, attribute the type A/B distinction to medial or final [[semivowel|glide]]s {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=55–57}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=32}} The diphthong proposals are often connected to hypotheses about pre-Old Japanese, but all exhibit an uneven distribution of glides.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=32}}
{| class="wikitable" |+ Examples of reconstructions of type A/B distinctions{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=62}} |- ! ''i''<sub>1</sub> !! ''i''<sub>2</sub> ! ''e''<sub>1</sub> !! ''e''<sub>2</sub> ! ''o''<sub>1</sub> !! ''o''<sub>2</sub> ! Author |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|wi}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|we}} || {{IPA|wo}} || {{IPA|o}} || Kikusawa (1935) |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|ï}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|ë}} || {{IPA|o}} || {{IPA|ö}} || Kindaichi (1938), Miller (1967) |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|ïj}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|əj}} || {{IPA|o}} || {{IPA|ə}} || Arisaka (1955) |- | {{IPA|ji}} || {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|je}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|o}} || {{IPA|ɵ}} || Hattori (1958) |- | {{IPA|ji}} || {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|je}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|wo}} || {{IPA|o}} || Lange (1968, 1973) |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|wi}} || {{IPA|je}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|wo}} || {{IPA|o}} || Unger (1977), Frellesvig and Whitman (2008) |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|ï}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|ɛ}} || {{IPA|o}} || {{IPA|ɵ}} || Ōno (1982) |- | {{IPA|i}} || {{IPA|ɨ}} || {{IPA|e}} || {{IPA|əj}} || {{IPA|o}} || {{IPA|ə}} || Miyake (2003) |}
The distinction between ''mo''<sub>1</sub> and ''mo''<sub>2</sub> is only seen in ''Kojiki'' and vanished afterwards. Distributionally, there may have once been *''po''<sub>1</sub>, *''po''<sub>2</sub>, *''bo''<sub>1</sub> and *''bo''<sub>2</sub>.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=30}} If this is true, then a distinction was made between C''o''<sub>1</sub> and C''o''<sub>2</sub> for all consonants C except for ''w''. Some take this as support that C''o''<sub>1</sub> may have represented C''wo''.
==== Pre-Old Japanese ====
Most scholars derive the Old Japanese vowel system from an earlier four-vowel system, with the most common Old Japanese vowels ''a'', ''u'', ''i''<sub>1</sub> and ''o''<sub>2</sub> reflecting earlier *a, *u, *i and *ə respectively.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=44}} [[Internal reconstruction]] suggests that the other, less common, Old Japanese vowels are derived from fusions of these vowels.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=80–81}} For example, the place name ''take''<sub>2</sub>''ti'' is derived from a compound of ''taka-'' 'high' and ''iti'' 'market'.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=81}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=46}} Another piece of evidence is that many nouns have different forms when used independently and when used within compounds. An example is ''sake''<sub>2</sub> 'rice wine', which becomes ''saka-'' in compounds such as ''sakaduki'' 'saké cup'. In such cases the bound form is considered basic, and the independent form may be explained by postulating a suffix *-i that fused with the final vowel of the root.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=80}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} The following reductions are proposed: * ''i''<sub>2</sub> < *ui: ''kami''<sub>2</sub>/''kamu''- 'god, spirit',{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=80}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} ''mi''<sub>2</sub>/''mu''- 'eye',{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}}{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=134}} ''nagi''<sub>2</sub>/''nagu''- 'a calm'.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=134}} * ''i''<sub>2</sub> < *əi: ''ki''<sub>2</sub>/''ko''<sub>2</sub>- 'tree',{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=80}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} ''yomi''<sub>2</sub>/''yomo''<sub>2</sub>- 'Hades'.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} * ''e''<sub>1</sub> < *ia: ''sake''<sub>1</sub>''ri'' 'blooming' < ''saki''<sub>1</sub> 'to bloom' + ''ari'' 'to be'.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=48}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=499}} * ''e''<sub>1</sub> < *iə: ''pe''<sub>1</sub>''ku'' (proper name) < ''pi''<sub>1</sub> 'sun' + ''o''<sub>2</sub>''ki''<sub>1</sub> 'put'.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=48}} * ''e''<sub>2</sub> < *ai: ''me''<sub>2</sub>/''ma''- 'eye',{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} ''ame''<sub>2</sub>/''ama''- 'heaven', ''ame''<sub>2</sub>/''ama''- 'rain', ''kage''<sub>2</sub>/''kaga''- 'shade'.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=133}} * ''o''<sub>1</sub> < *ua: ''kazo''<sub>1</sub>''pu'' 'to count' < ''kazu'' 'number' + ''apu'' 'to combine'.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=81}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=48}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=498–499}} * ''o''<sub>1</sub> < *uə: ''sito''<sub>1</sub>''ri'' 'kind of native weaving' < ''situ'' 'native weaving' + ''ori'' 'weaving'.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=81}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=48}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=498}} There are also alternations suggesting ''e''<sub>2</sub> < *əi, such as: * ''se''<sub>2</sub>/''so''<sub>2</sub>- 'back', ''me''<sub>2</sub>/''mo''<sub>2</sub>- 'bud'{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=45}} Some authors believe these belong to an earlier layer than ''i''<sub>2</sub> < *əi, while others reconstruct two central vowels *ə and *ɨ, which merge everywhere except before *i.{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=499}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=45–47}} Other authors attribute this variation to different reflexes in different dialects, noting that *əi yields ''e'' in [[Ryukyuan languages]].{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=661}} Some authors also suggest that *e and *o are required to account for word-final ''e''<sub>1</sub> and ''o''<sub>1</sub> respectively.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=47–48}}
===Consonants===
Miyake 2003 reconstructs the following inventory, in addition to a zero vowel-initial onset {{IPA|/∅/}}:{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=196}}
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;" |+ Old Japanese consonants ! colspan="2"| ! [[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! colspan="2" | [[Coronal consonant|Coronal]] ! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! [[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- ! rowspan="2"| [[Obstruent]] ! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | *{{IPAlink|p}} | *{{IPAlink|t}} | *{{IPAlink|s}} | | *{{IPAlink|k}} |- ! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]] [[prenasalized consonant|prenasalized]]}} | *{{IPA|ᵐb}} | *{{IPA|ⁿd}} | *{{IPA|ⁿz}} | | *{{IPA|ᵑɡ}} |- ! colspan="2"| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | *{{IPAlink|m}} | colspan=2| *{{IPAlink|n}} | | |- ! colspan="2"| [[Liquid consonant|Liquid]] | | colspan=2| *{{IPA|r}}<!-- It is inappropriate to link this to the article on any particular sound because the realization is not clear. --> | | |- ! colspan="2"| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | *{{IPA link|w}} | colspan=2| | *{{IPA link|j}} | |}
The voiceless obstruents {{IPA|/p, t, s, k/}} had the voiced prenasalized counterparts {{IPA|/ᵐb, ⁿd, ⁿz, ᵑɡ/}}.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=196}} This prenasalization was still present in the late 17th century (according to the Korean textbook ''Chephay sine''), and is found in some modern Japanese and Ryukyuan dialects, but has disappeared in Modern Japanese, except for the intervocalic nasal stop allophone {{IPA|[ŋ]}} of {{IPA|/ɡ/}}.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=75–76}} The sibilants {{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/ⁿz/}} may have been palatalized before ''e'' and ''i''.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=183, 186}}
Comparative evidence from [[Ryukyuan languages]] suggests that Old Japanese ''p'' derives from an earlier [[voiceless bilabial stop]] *p.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=194}} There is general agreement that word-initial ''p'' had become a [[voiceless bilabial fricative]] {{IPA|[ɸ]}} by Early Middle Japanese, as suggested by its transcription as ''f'' in later Portuguese works and as ''ph'' or ''hw'' in the Korean textbook ''Chephay sine''. In Modern Standard Japanese, it is romanized as ''h'' and has different [[allophone]]s before various vowels. In medial position, it became {{IPA|[w]}} in Early Middle Japanese, and has since disappeared except before ''a''.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=74}} Many scholars argue that ''p'' had already lenited to {{IPA|[ɸ]}} by the Old Japanese period, but Miyake argues that it was still a stop.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=71, 164–166}}
====Pre-Old Japanese==== Internal reconstruction suggests that the Old Japanese voiced obstruents, which always occurred in medial position, arose from weakening of earlier nasal syllables before voiceless obstruents:{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=73}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=42–43}} * ''b'' {{IPA|/ᵐb/}} < *-mVp-, *-nVp-: e.g. ''abi''<sub>1</sub>''ki''<sub>1</sub> 'trawling' < ''ami''<sub>1</sub> 'net' + ''pi''<sub>1</sub>''ki''<sub>1</sub> 'pull'. * ''d'' {{IPA|/ⁿd/}} < *-mVt-, *-nVt-: e.g. ''yamadi'' 'mountain path' < ''yama'' 'mountain' + ''mi''<sub>1</sub>''ti'' 'path'. * ''z'' {{IPA|/ⁿz/}} < *-mVs-, *-nVs-: e.g. the title ''murazi'' < ''mura'' 'village' + ''nusi'' 'master'. * ''g'' {{IPA|/ᵑɡ/}} < *-mVk-, *-nVk-. In some cases there is no evidence for a preceding vowel, leading some scholars to posit final nasals at the earlier stage.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=43}}
Some linguists suggest that Old Japanese ''w'' and ''y'' derive respectively from *b and *d at some point before the oldest inscriptions in the 6th century.{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=71–73}} [[Southern Ryukyuan languages|Southern Ryukyuan varieties]] such as [[Miyako language|Miyako]], [[Yaeyama language|Yaeyama]] and [[Yonaguni language|Yonaguni]] retain {{IPA|/b/}} and {{IPA|/d/}} in these words:{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=194}} * ''ba'' 'I' and ''bata'' 'stomach' corresponding to Old Japanese ''wa'' and ''wata'' * Yonaguni ''da'' 'house', ''du'' 'hot water' and ''dama'' 'mountain' corresponding to Old Japanese ''ya'', ''yu'' and ''yama'' However, many linguists, especially in Japan, argue that the Southern Ryukyuan voiced stops are local innovations.{{sfn|Vovin|2010|pp=36–44}} Some supporters of *b and *d also add *z and *g, both disappearing in Old Japanese, for reasons of symmetry.{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=666}} However, there is very little Japonic evidence for these.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=43}}{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=68–71}}
===Morphophonemics===
Vowel elision occurred to prevent vowel clusters. When a monosyllabic morpheme is followed by a polysyllabic morpheme beginning with a vowel, the second vowel is dropped:{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=662}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=39–40}} * ''wa'' + ''ga'' + ''ipe''<sub>1</sub> → ''wagape''<sub>1</sub> In other environments, the first vowel is dropped:{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=662}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=39–40}} * ''ake'' + ''u'' → ''aku'' * ''to''<sub>2</sub>''ko''<sub>2</sub> + ''ipa'' → ''to''<sub>2</sub>''kipa'' * ''ko''<sub>2</sub> + ''i'' → ''ki''
===Accent===
Although modern [[Japanese dialects]] have [[pitch accent]] systems, these are usually not shown in ''man'yōgana''. However, in one part of the ''Nihon Shoki'', the Chinese characters appear to be chosen to represent a pitch pattern similar to that recorded in the ''[[Ruiju Myōgishō]]'', a dictionary compiled in the late 11th century. In this section, a low pitch syllable is represented by a character with the [[Middle Chinese]] level tone, and a high pitch is represented by a character with one of the other three [[four tones (Middle Chinese)|Middle Chinese tones]]. (A similar division was used in the [[tone pattern]]s of Chinese poetry, which were emulated by Japanese poets in the late [[Asuka period]].) Thus it appears that the Old Japanese accent system was similar to that of [[Early Middle Japanese]].{{sfn|Miyake|2003|pp=37–39}}
==Grammar== {{expand section|date=November 2014}}
As in later forms of Japanese, Old Japanese word order was predominantly [[subject–object–verb]], with adjectives and adverbs preceding the nouns and verbs they modify, and [[auxiliary verb]]s and [[grammatical particle|particle]]s consistently appended to the main verb.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|pp=122–123}}
===Pronouns===
Many Old Japanese pronouns had both a short form and a longer form with attached ''-re'' of uncertain etymology. Where the pronoun occurred in isolation, the longer form would be used. With genitive particles or in nominal compounds, the short form was used, whereas in other situations either form was possible.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=136–137}}
[[Personal pronouns]] were distinguished by taking the [[genitive case|genitive]] marker ''ga'', in contrast to the marker ''no''<sub>2</sub> used with demonstratives and nouns.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=138}} * The first [[grammatical person|person]] pronouns were ''a(re)'' and ''wa(re)'', were used for the singular and plural respectively, though with some overlap. The ''wa-'' forms were also used [[reflexive pronoun|reflexive]]ly, suggesting that ''wa'' was originally an [[indefinite pronoun]] and gradually replaced ''a''.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=138}} * The second person pronoun was ''na(re)''.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=136}} * The third person pronoun ''si'' was much less commonly used than the non-proximal demonstrative ''so''<sub>2</sub>, from which it was derived.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=138–139}} * There were also an [[interrogative pronoun]] ''ta(re)'' and a reflexive pronoun ''o''<sub>2</sub>''no''<sub>2</sub>.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=136}}
[[Demonstrative]]s often distinguished proximal (to the speaker) and non-proximal forms marked with ''ko''<sub>2</sub>- and ''so''<sub>2</sub>- respectively. Many forms had corresponding interrogative forms ''i(du)-''.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=139–140}}
{| class="wikitable" |+ Old Japanese demonstratives{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=141}} |- ! !! Proximal !! Non-proximal !! Interrogative |- ! Nominal | ''ko''<sub>2</sub>(''re'') || ''so''<sub>2</sub> || ''idu''(''re'') |- ! Location | ''ko''<sub>2</sub>''ko''<sub>2</sub> || ''so''<sub>2</sub>''ko''<sub>2</sub> || ''iduku'' |- ! Direction | ''ko''<sub>2</sub>''ti'' || – || ''iduti'' |- ! Degree | ''ko''<sub>2</sub>''kV-'' || ''so''<sub>2</sub>''kV-'' || ''iku-'' |- ! rowspan="2" | Manner | ''ka'' || ''sate'' || – |- | ''kaku'' || ''sika'' || ''ika'' |- ! Time | – || – || ''itu'' |}
In Early Middle Japanese, the non-proximal ''so-'' forms were re-interpreted as hearer-based (medial), and the formerly speaker-based forms divided into proximal ''ko-'' forms and distal ''ka-''/''a-'' forms, yielding the three-way distinction still found in Modern Japanese.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=140, 246–247}}
=== Verbs ===
Old Japanese had a richer system of verbal suffixes than later forms of Japanese.{{sfn|Shibatani|1990|p=123}} Old Japanese verbs used [[inflection]] for [[linguistic modality|modal]] and [[conjunction (grammar)|conjunction]]al purposes.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=53}} Other categories, such as [[voice (grammar)|voice]], [[grammatical tense|tense]], [[grammatical aspect|aspect]] and [[grammatical mood|mood]], were expressed using optional suffixed [[auxiliary verb|auxiliaries]], which were also inflected.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=59}}
==== Inflected forms ====
As in later forms of Japanese, Old Japanese verbs had a large number of inflected forms. In traditional Japanese grammar, these are represented by six forms (''katsuyōkei'', 活用形) from which all the others may be derived, in a similar fashion to the [[principal parts]] used for [[Latin language|Latin]] and other languages:{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=114–118}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|未然形|Mizenkei}}'' (irrealis) :This form never occurs in isolation, but only as a stem to which several particles and auxiliaries are attached.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=111–112}} Unger calls it a "pseudostem", because the purported inflection was originally an initial *a of the suffixes attached to this stem.{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=665}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|連用形|Renyoukei}}'' (adverbial, infinitive) :This form was used as the [[infinitive]].{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=56–57}} It also served as a stem for auxiliaries expressing tense and aspect.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=109–111}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|終止形|Shushikei}}'' (conclusive, predicative) :This form was used as the main verb concluding a declarative sentence.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=53}} It was also used before modal extensions, final particles and some conjunctional particles.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=123–124, 133}} The conclusive form merged with the attributive form by about 1600, but the distinction is preserved in Ryukyuan languages and the [[Hachijōjima dialects]].{{sfnp|Shibatani|1990|pp=195, 207, 223–224}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|連体形|Rentaikei}}'' (attributive, adnominal) :This form was used as the verb in a nominalized clause or a clause modifying a noun.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=54–55}} It was also used before most conjunctional particles.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=133}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|已然形|Izenkei}}'' (realis, exclamatory, subjunctive) :This form was used as the main verb in an exclamatory sentence or as the verb in an adverbial clause.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=55}} It also served as a stem for the particles ''-ba'' (provisional) and ''-do'' (concessive).{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=112–113}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|命令形|Meireikei}}'' (imperative) :This form expressed the [[imperative mood]].{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=55}} This system has been criticized because the six forms are not equivalent, with one being solely a combinatory stem, three solely word forms, and two being both. It also fails to capture some inflected forms. However, five of the forms are basic inflected verb forms, and the system also describes almost all extended forms in a consistent way.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=116–118}}
==== Conjugation classes ====
Japanese verbs are classified into eight conjugation classes, each characterized by different patterns of inflected forms. Three of these classes are grouped as consonant bases:{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=96}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|四段活用|Yodan}}'' (quadrigrade) :This class of regular consonant-base verbs includes approximately 75% of verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=96}} The class is so named because the inflections in later forms of Japanese span four rows of a ''[[kana]]'' table, corresponding to four vowels. However, in Old Japanese five different vowels are involved.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=115}} These bases are almost all of the form (C)VC-, with the final consonant limited to ''p'', ''t'', ''k'', ''b'', ''g'', ''m'', ''s'' or ''r''.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=97}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|ナ行変格活用|Na-hen}}'' (''n''-irregular) :The three ''n''-base verbs form a class of their own: ''sin-'' 'die', ''-in-'' 'depart' and the auxiliary ''-(i)n-'' expressing completion of an action. They are often described as a "hybrid" conjugation, because the adnominal and exclamatory forms follow a similar pattern to vowel-base verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=105}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|ラ行変格活用|Ra-hen}}'' (''r''-irregular) :The irregular ''r''-base verbs are ''ar-'' 'be, exist' and other verbs incorporating it, as well as ''wor-'' 'sit', which became the existential verb ''or-'' in later forms of Japanese.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=101–103}}
{| class="wikitable" |+ Conjugation of consonant-base verbs{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=54, 114}} |- ! Verb class ! Irrealis !! Infinitive !! Conclusive !! Adnominal !! Exclamatory !! Imperative ! Gloss |- ! Quadrigrade | ''kaka-'' | ''kaki''<sub>1</sub> | ''kaku'' | ''kaku'' | ''kake''<sub>2</sub> | ''kake''<sub>1</sub> | 'write' |- ! ''n''-irregular | ''sina-'' | ''sini'' | ''sinu'' | ''sinuru'' | ''sinure'' | ''sine'' | 'die' |- ! ''r''-irregular | ''ara-'' | ''ari'' | ''ari'' | ''aru'' | ''are'' | ''are'' | 'be, exist' |}
The distinctions between ''i''<sub>1</sub> and ''i''<sub>2</sub> and between ''e''<sub>1</sub> and ''e''<sub>2</sub> are lost after ''s'', ''z'', ''t'', ''d'', ''n'', ''y'', ''r'' and ''w''.
There are five vowel-base conjugation classes: ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|下二段活用|Shimo nidan}}'' (lower bigrade or ''e''-bigrade) :The largest regular vowel-base class comprises bases ending in ''e''<sub>2</sub>, and includes approximately 20% of verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=97}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|上二段活用|Kami nidan}}'' (upper bigrade or ''i''-bigrade) :This class of bases ending in ''i''<sub>2</sub> contains about 30 verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=97}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|上一段活用|Kami ichidan}}'' (upper monograde or ''i''-monograde) :This class contains about 10 verbs of the form (C)''i''<sub>i</sub>-. Some monosyllabic upper bigrade verbs had already shifted to this class by the Old Japanese period, and the rest followed in Early Middle Japanese.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=106}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|カ行変格活用|Ka-hen}}'' (''k''-irregular) :This class consists of the single verb ''ko''<sub>2</sub>- 'come'.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=107–108}} ;''{{wikt-lang|ja|サ行変格活用|Sa-hen}}'' (''s''-irregular) :This class consists of the single verb ''se-'' 'do'.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=107–108}} Early Middle Japanese also had a ''{{wikt-lang|ja|下一段活用|Shimo ichidan}}'' (lower monograde or ''e''-monograde) category consisting of a single verb ''kwe-'' 'kick', which reflects the Old Japanese lower bigrade verb ''kuwe-''.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=227–228}}{{sfn|Yamaguchi|Suzuki|Sakanashi|Tsukimoto|1997|p=18}}{{sfn|Kondō|Tsukimoto|Sugiura|2005|p=41}}{{sfn|Omodaka|1967|pp=37–38}}
{| class="wikitable" |+ Conjugation of vowel-base verbs{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=54, 114}} |- ! Verb class ! Irrealis !! Infinitive !! Conclusive !! Adnominal !! Exclamatory !! Imperative ! Gloss |- ! ''e''-bigrade | ''ake''<sub>2</sub>- | ''ake''<sub>2</sub> | ''aku'' | ''akuru'' | ''akure'' | ''ake''<sub>2</sub> | 'open' |- ! ''i''-bigrade | ''oki''<sub>2</sub>- | ''oki''<sub>2</sub> | ''oku'' | ''okuru'' | ''okure'' | ''oki''<sub>2</sub> | 'arise' |- ! monograde | ''mi''<sub>1</sub>- | ''mi''<sub>1</sub> | ''mi''<sub>1</sub>''ru'' | ''mi''<sub>1</sub>''ru'' | ''mi''<sub>1</sub>''re'' | ''mi''<sub>1</sub>(''yo''<sub>2</sub>) | 'see' |- ! ''k''-irregular | ''ko''<sub>2</sub>- | ''ki''<sub>1</sub> | ''ku'' | ''kuru'' | ''kure'' | ''ko''<sub>2</sub> | 'come' |- ! ''s''-irregular | ''se-'' | ''si'' | ''su'' | ''suru'' | ''sure'' | ''se''(''yo''<sub>2</sub>) | 'do' |}
The bigrade verbs seem to belong to a later layer than the consonant-base verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=120}} Many ''e''-bigrade verbs are [[transitive verb|transitive]] or [[intransitive verb|intransitive]] counterparts of consonant-stem verbs.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=118–119}} In contrast, ''i''-bigrade verbs tend to be intransitive.{{sfn|Whitman|2008|p=164}} Some bigrade bases also appear to reflect pre-Old-Japanese adjectives with vowel stems combined with an [[inchoative verb|inchoative]] *-i suffix:{{sfn|Unger|2000|p=665}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=119}}{{sfn|Whitman|2008|p=165}} * *-a-i > ''-e''<sub>2</sub>, e.g. ''ake''<sub>2</sub>- 'redden, lighten' vs ''aka'' 'red'. * *-u-i > ''-i''<sub>2</sub>, e.g. ''sabi''<sub>2</sub>- 'get desolate, fade' vs ''sabu-'' 'lonely'. * *-ə-i > ''-i''<sub>2</sub>, e.g. ''opi''<sub>2</sub>- 'get big, grow' vs ''opo-'' 'big'.
===Adjectives=== {{refimprove section|date=November 2014}}
There were two types of adjectives: regular [[adjective]]s and [[adjectival noun (Japanese)|adjectival noun]]s.
The regular adjective is sub-classified into two types: those where the adverbial form ({{lang|ja|連用形}}) ends in ''-ku'' and those that end in ''-siku.'' This creates two different types of conjugations:
{| class=wikitable |- ! Adjective Class ! [[wiktionary:未然形|Irrealis]] ! [[wiktionary:連用形|Adverbial]] ! [[wiktionary:終止形|Conclusive]] ! [[wiktionary:連体形|Attributive]] ! [[wiktionary:已然形|Realis]] ! [[wiktionary:命令形|Imperative]] |- ! rowspan=2| ''-ku'' | ''-ke''<sub>1</sub> | ''-ku'' | ''-si'' | ''-ki''<sub>1</sub> | ''-ke''<sub>1</sub><br>''-ke''<sub>1</sub>''re'' | &nbsp; |- | ''-kara'' | ''-kari'' | ''-si'' | ''-karu'' | ''-kare'' | ''-kare'' |- ! rowspan=2| ''-siku'' | ''-sike''<sub>1</sub> | ''-siku'' | ''-si'' | ''-siki''<sub>1</sub> | ''-sike''<sub>1</sub><br>''-sike''<sub>1</sub>''re'' | &nbsp; |- | ''-sikara'' | ''-sikari'' | ''-si'' | ''-sikaru'' | ''-sikare'' | ''-sikare'' |}
The ''-kar-'' and ''-sikar-'' forms are derived from the adverbial conjugation (''-ku'' or ''-siku'') suffixed with verb ''ar-'' "be, exists". The conjugation yields to the R-irregular conjugation of ''ar-''. As Old Japanese avoids vowel clusters, the resulting ''-ua-'' is reduced to ''-a-''.{{sfn|Bentley|2012|p=197}}
The adjectival noun has a single conjugation:
{| class=wikitable |- ! &nbsp; ! [[wiktionary:未然形|Irrealis]] ! [[wiktionary:連用形|Adverbial]] ! [[wiktionary:終止形|Conclusive]] ! [[wiktionary:連体形|Attributive]] ! [[wiktionary:已然形|Realis]] ! [[wiktionary:命令形|Imperative]] |- ! Adjectival noun | ''-nara'' | ''-nari'' | ''-nari'' | ''-naru'' | ''-nare'' | ''-nare'' |}
==Dialects== Although the majority of Old Japanese writing represents the language of the [[Nara, Nara|Nara]] court in central Japan, some sources come from eastern Japan:{{sfn|Vovin|2005}}{{sfn|Miyake|2003|p=159}}{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=23–24, 151}} * 230 ''azuma uta'' 'eastern songs' in volume 14 of the ''Man'yōshū'', * 93 ''sakimori uta'' 'borderguard songs' in volume 20 of the ''Man'yōshū'', and * 9 songs in the ''Hitachi [[fudoki]]'' (714–718). They record Eastern Old Japanese dialects,{{sfn|Kupchik|2011}} with features such as: * There is no type A/B distinction on front vowels ''i'' and ''e'', though ''o''<sub>1</sub> and ''o''<sub>2</sub> are distinguished.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=152}} * Pre-Old Japanese *ia yielded ''a'' in the east, where Central Old Japanese has ''e''<sub>1</sub>.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=152}} * The adnominal form of consonant-base verbs ended in ''-o''<sub>1</sub>, where Central Old Japanese has ''-u'' as in the conclusive form.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|pp=152–153}} A similar difference is preserved in [[Ryukyuan languages]], suggesting that Central Old Japanese had innovated by merging these endings.{{sfn|Bentley|2012|p=189}} * The imperative form of vowel-base verbs attached ''-ro''<sub>2</sub>, instead of the ''-yo''<sub>2</sub> used in Central Old Japanese.{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=153}} * There are a group of distinctive negative auxiliaries. However, they do not seem to be the source of the different negatives in modern eastern and western [[Japanese dialects]].{{sfn|Frellesvig|2010|p=153}}
