As of 2015, there were at least four translations of the [[Tirukkural]] available in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].
==History of translations== The first Bengali translation was made in prose by Nalini Mohan Sanyal in 1939. It was published by Bangiya Sahitya Parishad, with a foreword by the eminent Bengali Scholar Dr. Suniti Kumar Chatterjee. However, the work is presently out of print, with the only copy available at the [[National Library of India|National Library]] in [[Kolkata]].<ref name="TK_SeminarPapers">{{cite book | last = Sanjeevi (Ed.) | first = N. | author-link = | title = First All India Tirukkural Seminar Papers | publisher = University of Madras | series = | volume = | edition = 2 | date = 1973 | location = Chennai | pages = 5–9 | language = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> The second translation was by E. C. Sastri in 1974, and the third translation appeared in 1993 by N. Ramanuja Das. The second and third translations too were made in prose. There appears to be another translation by T. N. Senapathy, the details of which are not known. The first verse translation was made by S. Krishnamoorthy, who has also translated ''[[Silappatikaram|Cilappadikaaram]]'' into English published by M. P. Birla Foundation, [[Kolkata]].<ref name="OOCities_Bengali">{{cite web |url = http://geocities.com/nvkashraf/kur-trans/Beng-Int.htm |title = Thirukkural in Bangla |last = Ashraf |first = N. V. K. |date = June 2005 |website = GeoCities |publisher = |access-date = 22 April 2017 |deadurl = bot: unknown |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091027145956/http://geocities.com/nvkashraf/kur-trans/Beng-Int.htm |archivedate = 27 October 2009 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>
